text":".","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In Microsoft’s compiler, by default struct stat means one with"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"64-bit time fields while in MinGW struct stat is the legacy one","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"with 32-bit fields. To hopefully clear up this messs, the gstdio.h","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"header defines a type "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/StatBuf","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" which is the appropriate struct type"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"depending on the platform and\/or compiler being used. On POSIX it","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"is just struct stat, but note that even on POSIX platforms, "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"stat()"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"might be a macro.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"See your C library manual for more details about ","type":"text"},{"code":"stat()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"kind":"content"}],"abstract":[{"text":"A wrapper for the POSIX ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"stat()"},{"type":"text","text":" function. The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"stat()"},{"text":" function","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"returns information about a file. On Windows the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"stat()"},{"type":"text","text":" function in"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the C library checks only the FAT-style READONLY attribute and does","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"not look at the ACL at all. Thus on Windows the protection bits in","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"st_mode"},{"type":"text","text":" field are a fabrication of little use."}],"sections":[],"kind":"symbol","schemaVersion":{"mino